text: hi everyone anthony fantano here
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new let live
album the blackest beautiful let liv
california rock band who for a few
albums now have been bringing together
elements of punk music metal music post
hardcore on top of that maybe some
modern pop punk flavors as well which
did play a pretty notable role on their
previous lp through some of the vocal
harmonies the really hooky choruses but
still with a lot of very just uh
aggressive
riffage just chop the [ __ ] up kind of
riffs
there was
an undeniable ferocity to this lp let
live is a really energetic band that i
think asks a lot of energy from its
listeners and and there are few things
in their sound that display that more
than the vocals which for the most part
are screamed and are really high volume
relentless impassioned put those
together with a really fast and tight
playing with the guitars and the drums
and somebody listening to this is is
bound to get hyped up now personally i i
do find let lives sound and just the way
that they deliver their songs to be a
little too clean for me a little too
clean in comparison with some of my
favorite post hardcore records out there
however i i wouldn't really say that
they're up there with some of the more
melodramatic
poppy and kind of [ __ ] and span bands in
the genre i don't know asking alexandria
and even though that's not the case uh
i gotta say i feel like let live is
moving a little bit further in that
direction with the blackest beautiful
oddly enough though i don't really feel
like the band has gotten any less
aggressive on this lp their front man
jason butler feels just as intense as he
did on the band's last full length he's
spazzing out on nearly every track here
his shouts and his screams feel really
throaty and when he goes for more of a
toned down spoken word kind of vibe he
feels really emotive kind of eccentric
over the top i think he has a ton of
personality as a front man even if
sometimes his lyrics don't really move
me or anything like that even if i may
agree with them to a slight degree the
american government is sucking the dicks
of corporations despite statements like
that i can't help but feel like
the sound that let liv presents at times
feels a tad bit corporate for one the
really clean robotic and pristine vocal
harmonies that are used on almost every
track on this lp
feel more than ever as if they're being
used just for accessibility purposes
because they certainly don't sound that
great for anybody that wants to just
hear a raw
natural real human voice it feels really
fake and obnoxious it's like the kind of
studio trickery that a really bad glam
metal band would use or even a new metal
band there are spots where butler's
vocalizations make me imagine him as
like a tiny david draymond i'm just torn
on his performances because for the most
part i feel like he is the most
interesting thing this album has to
offer because of his energy and because
of his passion aside from anthony rivera
on drums who actually has a fantastic
drum break on the track the fear fever
but consistently throughout the album
his grooves his his tightness his speed
and his detail are all really impressive
even though butler seems like an
incredibly capable singer obviously
that's the case from letlip's previous
lp
every time he tries to do something that
seems to stick out on here it just makes
me cringe a little bit like the start of
the track white america i told him like
this or the the really sort of overacted
and whimpering vocals on
the closer especially as he's kind of
talking about taking his own life and
kind of laughing to himself toward the
very back end of the track as if this is
like some kind of display of psychosis
or maybe he's being maniacal i'm i'm not
sure i just feel ambivalent toward most
of the emotions that let live just
throws up in
the lyrics to be completely honest and
and i i don't think the band is
necessarily over emotive i get that post
hardcore is music that has a lot of
links to
emo music and and other very expressive
forms of punk my issue is that i just
really can't say there's much of
anything about let liv's approach that
feels fresh for sure their intensity
makes it adequate the performances on
this record are really tight the
production of post-production i feel
have essentially given us a record that
is really heavy and technically flawless
the band plays well and in some of their
more sporadic moments they remind me of
groups like blood brothers or the
refused and as much as i like the spots
on this album that remind me of those
groups the more that i think about it
and the more that i listen to this
the more this album feels like just an
unapologetically
poppy bastardization of the sounds that
influence it and i don't really have
anything against perfection or
accessibility for sure everything on the
new queens of the stone age record shows
up on time so to speak but that album
even though it's catchy it's it's
somewhat subversive and it's in its
really moody emotions on the black is
beautiful let live definitely comes off
as as fast and abrasive
but it's almost kind of misleading
because once you dig past that i feel
like i'm listening to these kind of
basic but sped up rock ballads which
lyrically a lot of the time i feel like
are just trying to plug into these
really vague appeals to
emotional emptiness or
some kind of discontent with the world
at large truth be told even though there
wasn't much on this record that offended
me or that i really disliked aside from
just the really cold sounding background
vocals a lot of it was just kind of dull
for me again i like the sound i think
the production is is top-notch but the
songwriting just really didn't do much
of anything for me i'm feeling a strong
four to a light five on this album if
you've given it a listen what did you
think of it did you love it hate it why
what do you think i should review next
and that's it this review is my opinion
if you don't like it here's a straw i
want to give a shout out to my dog nori
get better
you're literally my dog only the strong
subscribe all mistakes were intentional
anthony fantano let live
forever
